  "text": "The Java security provider registration framework in openjdk/jdk consists of the following key files:\n\n1. **Base Provider class** (`src/java.base/share/classes/java/security/Provider.java`): Defines `java.security.Provider`, the abstract base class for all security providers. Contains the `putService()` method that providers use to register algorithm implementations.\n\n2. **SunJCE provider** (`src/java.base/share/classes/com/sun/crypto/provider/SunJCE.java`): The Sun Java Cryptography Extension provider that registers symmetric encryption algorithms (AES, DES, etc.), MACs, key generators, and other cryptographic services.\n\n3. **SunJSSE provider** (`src/java.base/share/classes/sun/security/ssl/SunJSSE.java`): The Sun Java Secure Socket Extension provider that registers SSL/TLS socket factories, key managers, and trust managers for secure communications.\n\n4. **SunEC provider** (`src/java.base/share/classes/sun/security/ec/SunEC.java`): The Sun Elliptic Curve provider that registers elliptic curve cryptography algorithms including ECDSA signature and ECDH key agreement.\n\n5. **Sun provider** (`src/java.base/share/classes/sun/security/provider/Sun.java`): The core Sun provider that registers fundamental algorithms like SHA message digests, DSA signatures, and secure random number generation.\n\n6. **ProviderConfig** (`src/java.base/share/classes/sun/security/jca/ProviderConfig.java`): The lazy-loading mechanism in `sun.security.jca` that maps provider names to their implementing classes and defers instantiation until the provider is first needed."
